{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3abfd980-9be3-4320-a0e0-a76eb8911005","content":"Since you're already on **MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0**, the change is minimal. MSTest.Sdk defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, and `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` is what opts you *out* of it.\n\n**What to change in your project file:**\n\n1. **Remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property.\n\nThat's it. MSTest.Sdk 3.4+ uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform by default.\n\n**Key behavioral differences to be aware of:**\n\n- **CLI:** Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test executable directly.\n- **`--filter`** syntax remains the same.\n- **Extensions** like code coverage or TRX reporting are now opt-in NuGet packages (e.g., `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`).\n- If you use a CI that parses VSTest TRX output, add:\n  ```xml\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n  ```\n  and pass `--report-trx` when running tests.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4f75f7af-829d-4494-a020-e5838d690708","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in their MSTest project. This is a knowledge-based question about .NET testing configuration. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.\n\nWhen using MSTest.Sdk, the switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform is straightforward:\n\n1. Remove `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` (or set it to `false`) from your project file\n2. Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default runner in MSTest.Sdk 3.4+\n\nLet me check if there's any relevant content in the repository that might help.","outputTokens":453,"requestId":"0BD6:33AAFA:2306AF:28C60B:69F00530"},"id":"e00a4b30-28b0-49cd-a090-c986894339d9","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:54:21.064Z","parentId":"41c73a01-c1b8-4687-889a-766dcce2c0f4"}
